n","1129":"1129","1080":"1080","1059":"1059","about 1080":"circa 1080","1063":"1063","Abt 1050":"circa 1050","1050":"1050","Brancepeth, Durham, England":"Brancepeth, Durham, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1050–":"about 1050–Deceased","1059–Female":"1059–Deceased","1063–Female":"1063–Deceased","1080–1129":"1080–1129","1050–Male":"1050–Deceased","1129":"1129","1080":"1080","1059":"1059","about 1080":"about 1080","1063":"1063","Abt 1050":"about 1050","1050":"1050","Brancepeth, Durham, England":"Brancepeth, Durham, England, United Kingdom","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Humez","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Durham): variant of   Hume  , with excrescent <i>-s</i>, or a variant of   Holmes  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hume","meanings":["Scottish (Lowlands) and northern English: variant of   Hulme  , with loss of <i>l</i> before the bilabial consonant /m/, as in the vocabulary word <i>calm</i>. See   Holm   and   Home  .","Scottish: habitational name either from the barony of Home or from Hume (or Home) in Berwickshire, from which the barony took its name. The placename derives from Old English <i>hōum</i>, dative plural form of <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’.","History: A family of this name (see 2 above) have held the Earldom of Home since 1605."]}]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Peter de Humez was born about 1050, in France."},"et":{"Abt 1050–":"umbes 1050–Surnud","1059–Female":"1059–Surnud","1063–Female":"1063–Surnud","1080–1129":"1080–1129","1050–Male":"1050–Surnud","1129":"1129","1080":"1080","1059":"1059","about 1080":"umbes 1080","1063":"1063","Abt 1050":"umbes 1050","1050":"1050","Brancepeth, Durham, England":"Brancepeth, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1050–":"noin 1050–Kuollut","1059–Female":"1059–Kuollut","1063–Female":"1063–Kuollut","1080–1129":"1080–1129","1050–Male":"1050–Kuollut","1129":"1129","1080":"1080","1059":"1059","about 1080":"noin 1080","1063":"1063","Abt 1050":"noin 1050","1050":"1050","Brancepeth, Durham, England":"Brancepeth, Durham, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"Abt 1050–":"environ 1050–Décédé","1059–Female":"1059–Décédée","1063–Female":"1063–Décédée","1080–1129":"1080–1129","1050–Male":"1050–Décédé","1129":"1129","1080":"1080","1059":"1059","about 1080":"environ 1080","1063":"